  "text": ", where ∆µ = µ r − R * µ t . For global similarity transformation, we detect critical landmarks by Speeded Up Robust Feature (SURF) detector [CITATION_1] . The detected tissue landmarks are then matched with local descriptors [CITATION_2] . Since many cellular features are at least 5 µm in diameter, corresponding landmarks, such as nuclei, exist in adjacent 5 µm thick sections. These landmarks help mitigate the \"banana\" reconstruction problem [CITATION_3] .",
